405	Root cause is in the server’s “JSONL as source of truth” sync combined with how temp `new_*` sessions are resolved. Deleting from the sidebar removes DB rows, but if the JSONL file is not actually removed, the next `/api/state` pass re‑imports it and the resolver can mis‑attach it to a new temp session.
406	
407	**Key mechanics in play**
408	- `/api/state` unconditionally re‑adds every `.jsonl` file it finds to the DB: it scans the sessions dir and `db.upsertSession(...)` for each file. That means any leftover JSONL will resurrect as a “zombie” even if it was deleted from the DB. `server.js:221` (JSONL → DB sync).
409	- The temp‑session resolver is order‑based and will match a `new_*` session to any “unmatched” JSONL file in that project. If a deleted session’s JSONL is still present, it becomes the first unmatched file and gets paired to the new temp session, effectively swapping the new session’s identity to the old one. `server.js:247-283` (stale `new_*` resolution). A similar arbitrary match happens in the background `resolveSessionId(...)` if `existingFiles` was stale. `server.js:1071+`.
410	- The UI simply calls DELETE then reloads state; it does not validate that the JSONL was actually removed, so any re‑import is immediately visible. `public/index.html:1232` and `public/index.html:676`.
411	
412	**Why JSONL might remain (and thus trigger the above)**
413	- Delete endpoint only tries to unlink a single path derived from the project name and `safe.findSessionsDir(...)`, then silently ignores failures. If the JSONL file path is wrong (project path mismatch, or CLI created the file in a different encoded dir), unlink fails and the JSONL survives. `server.js:452-476` + `safe-exec.js:185`.
414	- The external MCP delete tool reimplements the path encoding instead of using `safe.findSessionsDir(...)`, and it’s not Windows‑safe (only replaces `/`, not `\`). That can silently fail to delete the JSONL and cause the same resurrection behavior if external tools are used. `mcp-external.js:162-185`.
415	- If the tmux session isn’t actually killed (e.g., name mismatch or collision), Claude can keep writing/recreating the JSONL after deletion. The tmux name is derived from only the first 12 chars of the session ID; for `new_*` timestamp IDs this truncation is collision‑prone, which can lead to killing/renaming the wrong tmux session. `server.js:1263` + `safe-exec.js:97`. This won’t directly create zombies by itself, but it makes JSONL cleanup unreliable.
416	
417	**How this maps to the reported symptoms**
418	- **Zombie reappearance:** Delete removes DB rows, but leftover JSONL gets re‑imported on the next `/api/state` call, so deleted sessions re‑show up. `server.js:221-242` + `server.js:452-476`.
419	- **Identity swap:** When a new session is created, the stale resolver matches the new temp session to the first unmatched JSONL file—often the leftover file from a “deleted” session—so the new session shows the old name (“Lifecycle Test” instead of “General Work”). `server.js:247-283` and `server.js:1071+`.
420	
