283	**Findings**
284	- High: race between prompt injection and tmux rename can drop the initial prompt. `setTimeout(..., 2000)` sends to `tmux` at the same time `resolveSessionId` starts its first poll/rename (`sleep(2000)`), so if JSONL appears quickly the session may be renamed before `tmuxSendKeys` runs, causing a send failure and lost prompt. `server.js:372` + `server.js:1078`
285	- Medium: `tmux send-keys` treats arguments as key names when they match. A user prompt like `C-c`, `Enter`, `C-m`, etc. can be interpreted as control keys rather than literal text, leading to unintended behavior (canceling input, submitting early, etc.). Use of `send-keys` without `-l` makes this possible. `safe-exec.js:123` + `server.js:374`
286	- Medium: prompt validation only exists client-side. If another client posts a whitespace prompt (e.g., `"   "`), `prompt` is truthy so the auto-name becomes `''` after `.trim()`, yielding an empty session name in DB/UI. `server.js:367`
287	- Low: modal uses fixed IDs `new-session-prompt`/`new-session-submit`, so opening multiple modals (double-click “New Session”, or rapid clicks) can create duplicate IDs and event handlers targeting the first element, leading to wrong prompt submission or stuck UI. `public/index.html:882` + `public/index.html:897`
